# I am learning Maestro autonomously

When a Maestro/QA failure is **demonstrated** in this repo (artifact, hierarchy,
log line, or user-confirmed recovery), you **must** record it — do not keep the
lesson only in chat memory.

Lexicon and bans: `.cursor/rules/no-probability-coding.mdc` (**Supposition**,
**Démonstration**, **Improvisation**). Skill files must not use the banned
words; code changes must not be done “on the fly” without established cause.

## Authorized action

You are **explicitly permitted** to edit:

`.cursor/skills/maestro-scenario-avoid-carpet-tripping/SKILL.md`

Add a short **error case not to repeat** with its solution **only after
demonstration**. Prefer a dedicated subsection so entries stay scannable.

## When a solution may be labeled established

**Wait** for at least one of:

1. A scenario (or slice) **log / artifact** showing the recovery — for a full
   orchestrator success, prefer a final line containing **`PASSED`** (see
   `maestro-scenario-avoid-carpet-tripping/SKILL.md`), or
2. Explicit **user confirmation** that the recovery worked.

Writing a skill entry that claims the fix **before** (1) or (2) is a
**supposition** (hypothèse / conjecture without positive proof) — **forbidden**.
You may implement a code change when the **cause** is established (see
`no-probability-coding.mdc`); you still must **not** promote that change to a
skill “established solution” until demonstration.

## Alternative solutions (same class of failure)

You **may** add an **alternative demonstrated** solution when a solution already
in the skill **worked before** but **fails in a new run** (different situation).

1. **Never delete** a previously demonstrated solution — keep it as historical /
   situational guidance.
2. Append the new solution next to it (or as a sibling bullet), labeled as an
   alternative.
3. If you **can identify** why the old solution did not apply this time, **write
   that situation difference** explicitly (mid-run vs fresh AVD, Semantics under
   `ScrollView` vs `AppBar.actions`, etc.).
4. If you **cannot** name the difference yet, still add the alternative that
   recovered **this** run, and note `situation difference: unknown — …`
   (evidence pointer) instead of inventing one.

## Hard gates

| Allowed | Forbidden |
| --- | --- |
| Cause established this run (log, hierarchy, screenshot) before **code** edit | Patch “to try” without established cause |
| Skill lesson only after green run log or user confirmation | Skill claim of success before demonstration |
| Smallest lesson: symptom → action → evidence pointer | Rewriting the whole skill or unrelated sections |
| Alternate fix + situation delta after **that** fix is demonstrated | Deleting or overwriting a prior demonstrated solution |

## When to write a skill entry

1. A recovery **works** and is **shown** in log/artifact or confirmed by the user, or
2. Hierarchy/`tapOn` COMPLETED vs UI proven in artifact; the **fix** is then
   demonstrated on a subsequent green run (or user confirms), or
3. A skill solution that **used to work** fails; a different recovery is
   **demonstrated** this run → append alternative (never remove the old one).

If evidence is missing, investigate first — **do not** invent a new skill entry.

## Relation to other rules

Complements `no-probability-coding.mdc` and `no-blind-patching-evidence-first.mdc`.
